metadata.name: Ganymede #38
metadata.description:
Ganymede is the largest moon in the Solar System, and nearly as large as the Earth. Its surface exhibits many fine cracks and fissures, thought to be caused by tidal heating due to the influence of nearby Jupiter. But, on closer inspection, one may see the effects of life on the surface patterning. In this animation, we see first an initial outward wave of activity, followed by a period of vigorous bubbling of interactive competition, and then finally intelligent structuring of the surface, leaving behind arcane symbols etched in the ice.

Programmed with vanilla javascript and the FastNoiseLite package.

Press "s" to save the image as a png file.

metadata.name: Segments #309
metadata.description:
A continuous flowing motion of segmented cubes.

There is 5 routes for variations which is chosen by the 'Animation Type' variable. Each route then has it's own way to produce variety based on the random values injected into each.

Routes available (each is a type of noise used to change the animation of the cubes):
1. Waveform
2. Cellular
3. Voronoise
4. Polka Dots
5. Layers

Each route then has between 5 to 11 variables that will change the outcome of the overall look.

metadata.name: LandWaves #228
metadata.description:
Reaction diffusion systems are mathematical representations of the behaviours of fluids that can be found in nature. A key characteristic of these systems is that the initial parameters are simple but the resulting process can be extremely complex. In LandWaves, pixel colours affect each other, line by line, from top to bottom. Frequencies of multiple oscillating sound waves are turning the brightness values of these pixels into sonic materia. 

This piece started as an experimentation in gallery spaces, then transformed over several different digital ecosystems, questioning their hyper-capitalist nature and mediated affordance.

Touch to listen

metadata.name: Alien Cities #63
metadata.description:
Alien Cities depicts fictional cities as they might look on another planet. Alien Cities are fractals, and can seem semi organic in nature. However, if you look close, you can see that each structure is sealed off from the atmosphere, showing its artificial nature.

Since Alien cities are a fractal, they have an almost infinite number of variations. In fact, taming the variability is one of the biggest challenges when using fractals. 

Alien Cities is coded using shaders, so it renders instantaneously on any size screen. The default view is gpu friendly, in that it will stop redrawing after a second or two. However, a gpu is recommended since it is a shader. See below about using the camera.

Variations:

- 22 hand tuned palettes.
- Fx, Fy, Fz control height and x/y spread of features.
- Angle controls the angles of the fractal folds. This has a large effect on the overall look of the city. If you get an angle close to a multiple of 90, the city will look much like a normal city block.
- Radius controls the size of the features in the fractal, and has a large effect on the height of the features.
- Being a fractal ensures all cities will be unique.

Keys: 

's' saves a png in the exact size of the screen.

Camera:

If you add ?allowCamera=1 to the url after you open it in a separate browser window, you can use the camera. Note that this will constantly use gpu resources, as it is redrawing every frame. If you minimize the browser window, chrome is smart enough to stop rendering.

The camera is an orbit camera with the following controls:

- left mouse drag rotates the scene around the center.
- right mouse drag pans the scene (moves the center of the scene).
- mouse wheel zooms in and out.

Zooming out will show the entire city as an island floating in space. Zooming in will show the details of the fractal, which can be quite intricate.

metadata.name: Circumscript #42
metadata.description:
It has always been a goal of mine to incorporate the worlds of physical and digital art together in a piece. And with circumscript I am the closest I've ever been. Circumscript uses a custom shader written to mix and "dilute" the colors on the canvas, thus creating a very physical feeling piece.

This dilution can be more or less depending on the edition, but always plays a huge role in the feel of the piece.


Happy new year.


----


[m] or [double tap] : opens the export/settings menu, use this menu to change the resolution, and make sure to press the reload button if you do.
[holding down] : zooms in on a certain area of the piece, depending on where your mouse/finger is. Use this feature to expore the complex textures of the piece in more detail, it's highly recommended to do this on a higher resolution setting.

The outputs can vary slighty per device, as there's a slight difference in how certain math gets interpreted on different devices with shaders.


----


Made with p5.js and webgl by Wouter Missler in 2022/3.

metadata.description:
âš—ðŸ¦ ðŸŒŒâœ¨

The center of a digital, quantified space emits 2 560 000 particles through a sequence of expansions, contractions and perturbations. ðŸŒŒ

Once formed, the evolution of the Univercell can be observed through a series of animations in the manner of a documentary. ðŸŽ¥

Each Univercell is a unique random and deterministic composition. ðŸ”®

(Click â€˜openâ€™ and go fullscreen for best experienceÂ !)

ðŸŽ„ðŸŒŸðŸªðŸŒˆâ˜€




-----
* Mint preview *

Minter will get a 1920x1920 PNG bitmap and an infinite animation.

-----
* Technics *

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 â†’ 7680x4320) at 60FPS for infinite duration.

The physics algorithms take around 20 seconds to generate one Univercell. During generation, a progress indication in percentage is displayed.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL
- Unique generative and determinist animation (animation is seeded by the fxhash mint hash)
- Unlimited duration (no loop) / 6 documentary animations
- 20 seconds internal algorithm variations

-----
* Controls *

Keyboard "Space" : take a PNG capture of the current view frame (same ratio as window, max 1920x1080)

âš— Empiric mode (empiric=on / see URL modifiers below)
Wheel/pinch : zoom in/out to observe the Univercell on different scales
Right click + drag : move the observation area
Keyboard "R" : enable automatic rotation of view

-----
* URL modifiers *

"&empiric=on"
Turn off animations and display a Univercell that can be manually explored.

"&demo=on"
Reduce the cinematics duration to 5 seconds. Allows faster cycling through documentary phases.

"&random=on"
Randomize documentary sequences order.

metadata.name: Schematics #78
metadata.description:
These recovered schematics seem to be alien in nature. The technology is beyond our grasp, be we can infer these schematics generate structures. The schematic itself is encoded in the same common mathematical language as the structures it generates.

Responsive Rendering

Schematics is coded using shaders, and renders instantaneously on any size screen. It is also GPU friendly, in that it will not consume any gpu resource after the first frame is rendered.  Since it is a shader, a gpu is recommended.

Keys: 

's' saves a png in the exact size of the screen.
